Mitochondrial encephalomyopathy, lactic acidosis, and stroke-like episodes (MELAS) is a rare disorder that affects the mitochondria, leading to a range of symptoms including global developmental delay, intellectual disability, and seizures. It can also cause muscle weakness, ptosis, and nystagmus. The decreased activity of mitochondrial complex I and increased lactate levels are characteristic of this condition. MELAS syndrome is often associated with a poor prognosis and can be fatal.
6. Mitochondrial encephalomyopathy, lactic acidosis, and stroke-like episodes (MELAS) syndrome is a rare disorder that affects the mitochondria, leading to a range of symptoms including global developmental delay, intellectual disability, and seizures. It can also cause muscle weakness, ptosis, and optic atrophy. The decreased activity of mitochondrial complex I and increased circulating lactate concentration are characteristic of this condition. MELAS syndrome can also cause feeding difficulties and difficulty walking due to muscle weakness and spasticity. The exaggerated startle response and myoclonus are also common features of this condition. Strabismus and nystagmus can occur due to the involvement of the brainstem and cerebellum. Epilepsia partialis continua is a type of seizure that can occur in MELAS syndrome. The symptoms of MELAS syndrome can vary in severity and progression, but early diagnosis and treatment can help manage the condition.
